
	tinypf: not thread-safe, dprintf like library for x86_64

API
	* TINY_PF_LONG_BOOL_FMT: this macro is used to overwrite the default values of
	boolean values, by default they are 'T' for true and 'F' for false. If the macro
	is defined, the values will become 'true' for true and 'false' for false.

	* tiny_pf: actual function which performs the lexing, parsing, writing and return of
	the total number of bytes writen. Its main arguments are
	- rdi: fd
	- rsi: format string

SET UP
	This function depends on `xvargs` library (see NOTES) to handle variadic arguments, therefore
	once rdi and rsi were set up correctly, all of the other arguments shall be pushed into the stack
	in the order xvargs specifies.

	Since arguments are pushed onto the stack before the call, the stack pointer is left
	shifted after tiny_pf returns. The caller must restore %rsp by adding 8 bytes for
	each pushed argument, or by popping into scratch registers.

	                           # stack (low-to-high):
	pushq    $'A'              # | 'A' | <- maps to %c
	pushq    $10               # |  10 | <- maps to %d
	movl     $1, %edi          # fd = stdout
	leaq     .fmt(%rip), %rsi  # fmtstring
	call     tiny_pf
	addq     $16, %rsp         # restore stack: 2 args x 8 bytes

	Failure to clean up the stack will leave %rsp misaligned and may crash
	the program on subsequent calls or on exit.

	For a complete example

	.section .rodata
		.fmt: .string "|int: %d char: %c|\n"

	.section .text
	.globl _start
	_start:
		pushq   $'A'    # maps to %c
		pushq   $10     # maps to %d
		movl    $1, %edi
		leaq    .fmt(%rip), %rsi
		call    tiny_pf
		addq    $16, %rsp  # clean up the two pushed arguments

		movq    $60, %rax  # exit
		xorq    %rdi, %rdi
		syscall

USAGE
	The function parses the format string left to right. Regular characters are
	written directly to the output buffer. A `%` character introduces a format
	specifier.

	%FORMAT

	  %c        character (value from stack)
	  %s        null-terminated string (pointer from stack)
	  %d        signed 64-bit integer, base 10
	  %b        boolean (zero = false, non-zero = true)
	  %%        literal `%`

	ALIGNMENT

	  %<SIZE...  left-align (pad on the right)
	  %>SIZE...  right-align (pad on the left)

	SIZE is either a literal decimal number (e.g. `%<10d`) or `#` to read the
	alignment size from the variadic stack at runtime (e.g. `%>#s`).

	When `%` is followed by `<` or `>`, the parser reads SIZE, then expects a
	second format character from the FORMAT list above. An unrecognised format
	character (after `%` or after an alignment specifier) triggers a fatal error.

ERRORS
	tiny-pf has two fatal error conditions. In both cases the message is written
	to stderr (fd 2) and the process exits with code 1.

	  * "tiny-pf: unknown format!\n"
	    Raised when `%` is followed by a character that is not one of
	    `c`, `s`, `d`, `b`, `%`, `<` or `>`.

	  * "tiny-pf: invalid alignment specifier!\n"
	    Raised when `<` or `>` is followed by a character that is neither
	    a decimal digit [0-9] nor `#`.

