NOTES
	* Buffer: tiny-pf uses a 4,096-byte static output buffer. If accumulated
	  output exceeds this capacity, a mid-flush writes the buffer to `fd` and
	  resets the counter transparently, allowing arbitrarily large output.

	* Number conversion: `%d` uses a 32-byte scratch buffer for integer-to-
	  string conversion, limiting the maximum number of representable digits.

	* Boolean format: The `TINY_PF_LONG_BOOL_FMT` macro controls boolean output.
	  When undefined: `%b` prints "T" for true and "F" for false. When defined:
	  "true" and "false". The provided makefile defines this macro by default.

	* Stack arguments: tiny-pf uses `xvargs` (see SET UP) to walk variadic
	  arguments on the stack. Arguments must be pushed in reverse order
	  (rightmost first), as shown in the example.

	* Runtime alignment: When `#` is used as SIZE, tiny-pf pops the value from
	  the variadic stack via `xvargs_next`, consuming one extra argument per `#`.

	* Platform: x86_64 Linux only — uses `write` (syscall 1) and `exit`
	  (syscall 60) directly.

	* xvargs library: https://github.com/h0p3so/xvargs

